<header class="top">
  <span class="top__brand">OIATC · Member resource</span>
  <span><a href="/explainers/robinson-huron-treaty">Back to main explainer</a></span>
  <span class="top__meta">Updated 2026-05-16</span>
</header>

<main class="page">

  <section class="cover">
    <p class="cover__eyebrow">A companion to the RHT 2026 explainer</p>
    <h1 class="cover__title">Distribution models: <em>questions each model has to answer</em></h1>
    <p class="cover__lede">Three ways your community can distribute its share. None of them is automatically right. Each one has to answer the same fair-test question: does this work for the whole membership, including the roughly half of members who live off-reserve, and for the children not yet born?</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="takeaway">
      <p>This page does not argue for any model. It shows what each model is good at, and the hard question each model has to answer before it is fair.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>At a glance</h2>
    <p class="lede">Three approaches, same fair-test questions. Scroll right on mobile.</p>

    <div class="matrix-wrap">
      <table class="matrix">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>The question</th>
            <th>Per-capita</th>
            <th>Collective</th>
            <th>Hybrid</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th>Who gets cash directly?</th>
            <td>Every member, equal share</td>
            <td>No one. Funds go to programs or trust.</td>
            <td>Members get a portion; rest goes collective.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Off-reserve member access?</th>
            <td>Equal by default. Same dollar, anywhere.</td>
            <td>Only if programs are designed to reach off-reserve.</td>
            <td>Equal on the cash portion. Depends on design for the rest.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Future generations?</th>
            <td>Each member decides for their own family.</td>
            <td>Trust or programs preserve capital long-term.</td>
            <td>Trust portion preserves; cash portion is members' choice.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Who decides spending?</th>
            <td>Each member, once received.</td>
            <td>Chief and Council, trustees, program staff.</td>
            <td>Members on cash; Council on collective.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="matrix__hard">
            <th>The hard question</th>
            <td>How do big community-scale projects get funded?</td>
            <td>How do off-reserve members actually reach the programs?</td>
            <td>What is the split, and who decides it?</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="matrix-note">The hard-question row is what each model has to answer to be fair. Highlighted because it is the load-bearing question for that model.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The three approaches in plain language</h2>
    <div class="models">

      <div class="model">
        <p class="model__num">Model 01</p>
        <h3 class="model__name">Per-capita</h3>
        <div class="flow">
          <span class="flow__node">Settlement</span>
          <span class="flow__arrow">→</span>
          <span class="flow__node">Community</span>
          <span class="flow__arrow">→</span>
          <span class="flow__node flow__node--end">Every member</span>
        </div>
        <p class="model__pitch">Every registered member gets the same dollar amount. Nipissing First Nation is running per-capita distribution sessions for the returned legal fees through May 2026.</p>
        <div class="model__block">
          <p class="model__label">Questions to answer</p>
          <ul class="model__qs">
            <li>Future generations not yet members: how are they provided for?</li>
            <li>Members who need supports beyond cash: how are they helped?</li>
            <li>Big community projects: who funds them?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="model">
        <p class="model__num">Model 02</p>
        <h3 class="model__name">Collective</h3>
        <div class="flow">
          <span class="flow__node">Settlement</span>
          <span class="flow__arrow">→</span>
          <span class="flow__node">Community</span>
          <span class="flow__arrow">→</span>
          <span class="flow__node flow__node--end">Programs / trust</span>
        </div>
        <p class="model__pitch">Funds held by the community for programs, infrastructure, or a long-term trust. Wiikwemkoong placed the bulk into a 100-year trust, used ~$85M as collateral for a development in Edmonton, and pays a $10,000 holiday distribution from interest.</p>
        <div class="model__block">
          <p class="model__label">Questions to answer</p>
          <ul class="model__qs">
            <li>Off-reserve members: how do they reach on-reserve programs?</li>
            <li>Membership consent: how are decisions ratified, including off-reserve?</li>
            <li>Accountability: audits, reports, member votes year over year?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="model">
        <p class="model__num">Model 03</p>
        <h3 class="model__name">Hybrid</h3>
        <div class="flow">
          <span class="flow__node">Settlement</span>
          <span class="flow__arrow">→</span>
          <span class="flow__node">Community</span>
          <span class="flow__arrow">→</span>
          <span class="flow__node flow__node--end">Both</span>
        </div>
        <p class="model__pitch">A split between direct payments and collective use. Can be one-time (holiday distribution this year, rest into trust) or structured (fixed annual share plus programs).</p>
        <div class="model__block">
          <p class="model__label">Questions to answer</p>
          <ul class="model__qs">
            <li>What is the split, and who decides it?</li>
            <li>Do the collective questions still apply to that portion?</li>
            <li>Do the per-capita questions still apply to that portion?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The off-reserve question</h2>
    <p class="lede">Roughly half of most RHT communities' members live off-reserve. That fact does not pick a model. It sets a test every model has to pass.</p>

    <div class="split-vis">
      <div class="split-vis__bar" aria-label="Membership split, on-reserve and off-reserve, roughly half and half">
        <div class="split-vis__on">~50% on-reserve</div>
        <div class="split-vis__off">~50% off-reserve</div>
      </div>
      <p class="split-vis__legend">A typical RHT community's membership, approximate.</p>
      <p class="split-vis__test"><strong>The test:</strong> can a member in Sudbury, Toronto, or Edmonton participate on the same terms as a member who lives in the community?</p>
    </div>

    <p>Per-capita answers this by giving every member the same dollar. Collective answers it only if programs are designed to be accessible from anywhere: remote enrolment, electronic participation, communications that reach members wherever they live. Hybrid inherits both answers.</p>
    <p>This is the standard. It is not an argument for one model.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Six questions to take to your Chief and Council</h2>
    <p class="lede">Useful for any model. Not loaded against any approach.</p>
    <div class="ask">
      <ol>
        <li>What share of the past compensation and the returned legal fees has our community received so far, and where is it held?</li>
        <li>What is the distribution plan: per-capita, collective, hybrid, or undecided?</li>
        <li>If any portion goes to collective use, what programs does it fund, and how do off-reserve members access them?</li>
        <li>How is the membership consulted, and how are off-reserve members included in that consultation?</li>
        <li>Who is the trustee or administrator, and what are the reporting and audit obligations?</li>
        <li>How can a member see the current balance, the annual spending, and the planned spending?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

